00:02:25.290 --> 00:02:29.600
Tectonic Technologies is developing pressure-sensing
mats for virtual reality.

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:34.500
They use hundreds of small force plates - with
measured data sent to a computer that translates

00:02:34.500 --> 00:02:36.350
real-time reactions in the game.

00:02:36.350 --> 00:02:40.290
They’ve used it to simulate flying, bending,
shifting weight and stepping.

00:02:40.290 --> 00:02:43.780
And they hope to start selling these by the
end of 2016.

00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:48.390
Scientists from the National Institute of
Polar Research revived Antarctic tardigrades

00:02:48.390 --> 00:02:51.120
frozen for over 30 years.

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:56.310
Taken from frozen moss in 1983 and stored
at minus 20 degrees C, the samples were recently

00:02:56.310 --> 00:02:57.340
defrosted.

00:02:57.340 --> 00:03:02.080
The tardigrades essentially woke up from suspended
animation, ate some algae - and went on to

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:04.080
successfully reproduce.

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:05.400
So yeah.

00:03:05.400 --> 00:03:10.100
In the spirit of using robots to augment human
ability - researchers at Georgia Tech created

00:03:10.100 --> 00:03:11.380
a three armed drummer.

00:03:11.380 --> 00:03:16.390
The smart arm responds not only to gestures
but also the music it hears.

00:03:16.390 --> 00:03:20.640
So for example, if the drummer moves to play
the high hat - the smart arm adjusts to play

00:03:20.640 --> 00:03:21.910
the ride cymbal.

00:03:21.910 --> 00:03:27.960
The drummer scenario used as a proof of concept
because it's reliant upon precise, timed movements

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:32.790
but this idea could be eventually implemented
on doctors, mechanics, or technicians who

00:03:32.790 --> 00:03:34.320
could use an extra hand.

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:37.920
The next steps are to link the movements to
directly to the user’s brain.

